<h1>Peculiarities of the second declension</h1>

<p>The proper noun <i>Deus</i>, (God) has an irregular denclension, due to modifications occured in different ages:</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Case</th>
<th>Singular</th>
<th>Plural</th>
</tr>
</thead>

<thbody>
<tr>
<th>Nominative</th>
<td>dĕus</td> <td>dĕī (seldom), dĭī, dī</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Genitive</th>
<td>dĕī</td>
<td>dĕōrum, dĕum</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Dative</th>
<td>deō</td>
<td>dĕīs (seldom), dĭīs, dīs</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Accusative</th>
<td>deum</td>
<td>dĕōs</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Vocative</th>
<td>dĕus, dīvĕ (in poetry only)
</td><td>dĕī (soldem), dĭī, dī</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Ablative</th>
<td>deo</td>
<td>dĕīs (seldom), dĭīs, dīs</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>The vocative singular of <i>deus</i> does not occur in classic Latin, but is said to have been dee; deus (like the nominative) occurs in the Vulgate; deus (like the nominative) appeared in the Vulgate. For the genitive plural, dīvum or dīvom, dīvus  divine) is often used.</p>

<p>Deus meus!, Mi Deus! («O my God!»);</p>
<p>Mi bone Deus! («O my good God!»);</p>

<p>The <b>genitive singular</b> of nouns ending in <b>-ĭus</b> and <b>-ĭum</b> in the nominative singularis irregular; along with the ending in <b>-ii</b>, they can also end in <b>-ī</b>;</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Nominative singular</th> <th>Genitive singular</th></tr>
</thead>

<thbody>
<tr><td>Vergilĭus </td>  <td>Vergil-ii / Vergìl-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gregorius</td> <td>Gregoii/Gregori</td></tr>
<tr><td>Aemilĭus</td>  <td>Aemil-ii / Aemìl-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tullĭus</td> <td> Tull-ii / Tull-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>filius</td>  <td>fil-ii / fil-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>negotium</td>  <td>negot-ii / negot-ī</td></tr>
</thbody>

</table>

<p>The <b>vocative singular</b>, of proper names of persons whose nominative end in <b>-ĭus</b> with a short ĭ, have the vocative singualr ending in <i>ī</i>, rather than in -ie.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Nominative singular</th> <th>Vocative singular</th></tr>
</thead>

<thbody>
<tr><td>Mercurĭus, -ii, m.</td> <td>Mercùr-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>Marĭus, -ii, m. </td> <td> Mar-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antonius, -ii, m.</td> <td>Anton-ī</td></tr>
<tr><td>filius, -ii, m.</td> <td>fil-ī</td></tr>
</thbody>

</table>

<p>Those with a long <i>ī</i>, like Darīus are regular, so the vocative singular is Darīe.</p>

<p>Also the masculine vocative singular of the possesive adjective <i>meus</i> is <i>mi</i>.</p> <p>fili mi! - oh, my son.</p>

